VALUES
(20, 10, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'The fear of the wicked, it shall come upon him:', 0, 47, 'question', 'Fear''s Reflection', 'In what ways do the fears of the wicked manifest in their lives? How does this understanding influence our approach to living righteously and confronting our own fears?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'but the desire of the righteous shall be granted.', 48, 97, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Desire''', 'שָׁאַל (sha''al, H7592) - to ask, inquire, or request. This Hebrew term suggests a deep longing for something beneficial, indicating that the desires of the righteous are not merely selfish but aligned with God''s will. This enriches our understanding of the righteousness that leads to granted desires.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H7592", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word used for ''desire''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'As the whirlwind passeth, so is the wicked no more', 0, 50, 'connection', 'Transience of the Wicked', 'This phrase parallels Job 21:18, which states, ''They are like straw before the wind, and like chaff that the storm carries away.'' Both verses emphasize the fleeting nature of the wicked, highlighting that their existence is temporary compared to the enduring presence of the righteous. Understanding this connection reinforces the theme of divine justice in Scripture.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Job 21:18", "description": "Job reflects on the fate of the wicked."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'but the righteous is an everlasting foundation', 52, 98, 'theology', 'Eternal Stability of the Righteous', 'Many scholars believe that the concept of the righteous as a ''foundation'' relates to the covenantal promises of God. In Matthew 7:24-25, Jesus speaks of the wise man who builds his house on the rock, illustrating that true stability and security are found in obedience to God''s word. This passage suggests that the righteous not only endure but also provide stability for others.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'As the whirlwind passeth, so is the wicked no more', 0, 50, 'question', 'Understanding Wickedness', 'What does it mean for the wicked to be ''no more''? How does this truth inform your understanding of justice in your own life or community? Reflecting on the temporality of evil can lead to a deeper appreciation of God''s ultimate justice and the hope found in righteousness.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'As vinegar to the teeth, and as smoke to the eyes,', 0, 50, 'connection', 'Sensory Analogies in Scripture', 'The use of sensory imagery in Proverbs 10:26 is echoed in other passages, such as Proverbs 25:20, which states, ''Like one who takes away a garment on a cold day, is one who sings songs to a heavy heart.'' Both verses illustrate how actions can produce discomfort or irritation. This connection highlights the importance of considering the feelings of others, especially in our relationships and responsibilities.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 25:20", "description": "Another verse using sensory imagery to convey relational truths."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'so is the sluggard to them that send him.', 51, 92, 'theology', 'The Value of Diligence', 'This passage suggests that laziness is not just a personal failing, but it impacts community and relationships. Many scholars believe this reflects the biblical view that work is a form of stewardship and responsibility towards others. The sluggard''s lack of diligence creates frustration for those who depend on him, aligning with the broader biblical teaching on the virtue of hard work (Colossians 3:23).', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Colossians 3:23", "description": "Encouragement for diligent work as an act of service."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'As vinegar to the teeth, and as smoke to the eyes,', 0, 50, 'question', 'Understanding Discomfort', 'What does it reveal about our responsibilities to others when we consider the discomfort caused by a sluggard''s actions? Reflecting on this verse, how can we ensure that our efforts contribute positively to those who rely on us?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 27, 27, 'kjv', 'The fear of the Lord prolongeth days', 0, 36, 'theology', 'The Value of Reverence', 'This phrase emphasizes the protective and life-extending nature of reverence towards God, suggesting a deep spiritual and ethical dimension to longevity. Many scholars believe this aligns with the concept of wisdom literature, where a proper relationship with God leads to a fuller life. The fear of the Lord is often seen as the beginning of wisdom (Proverbs 9:10), highlighting the interconnectedness of spiritual reverence and practical living.', 'person.2.fill', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 27, 27, 'kjv', 'but the years of the wicked shall be shortened', 38, 84, 'connection', 'Consequences of Wickedness', 'This phrase connects to Psalm 55:23, which states that the wicked will not live out half their days. It emphasizes the temporal consequences of a life lived in opposition to God. The connection matters because it reinforces the idea that wickedness ultimately leads to self-destruction, contrasting sharply with the longevity promised to the righteous, and serves as a moral warning.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 55:23", "description": "This verse echoes the theme of the consequences of wickedness."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 27, 27, 'kjv', 'The fear of the Lord prolongeth days', 0, 36, 'question', 'Understanding Fear of God', 'What does it mean to truly fear the Lord, and how does this reverence influence your daily choices? Reflect on specific instances where acknowledging God''s authority in your life has led to positive outcomes or decisions.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 27, 27, 'kjv', 'but the years of the wicked shall be shortened', 38, 84, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Shortened''', 'שָׁנָה (shanah, H8141) - year, age, period. This term conveys not just a measure of time but also the quality of life experienced during that time. The implication is that the life of the wicked, though it may be of a certain length, is ultimately lacking in fulfillment and joy.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H8141", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term used."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 28, 28, 'kjv', 'The hope of the righteous shall be gladness', 0, 43, 'connection', 'Hope and Joy Connection', 'This phrase parallels Psalm 146:5, which states, ''Blessed is he whose help is the God of Jacob, whose hope is in the Lord his God.'' Both verses emphasize the joy derived from hope founded in righteousness and trust in God, highlighting how true gladness comes from a relationship with Him.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 146:5", "description": "Illustrates the relationship between hope and divine blessing."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 28, 28, 'kjv', 'the expectation of the wicked shall perish', 49, 91, 'theology', 'Righteousness vs. Wickedness', 'Many scholars believe this verse reflects the biblical theme of divine justice, illustrating that while the righteous can expect joy, the wicked''s hopes are ultimately hollow and doomed to fail. This aligns with the broader theological understanding that God''s justice prevails, and righteousness leads to lasting fulfillment.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Proverbs 11:7", "description": "Highlights the futility of the wicked''s aspirations."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 28, 28, 'kjv', 'The hope of the righteous shall be gladness', 0, 43, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Hope''', 'אֶלְפָּיִשׁ (elpis, H8420) - hope, expectation. This term signifies a confident expectation or trust. In the context of righteousness, it suggests that the hope of the righteous is not merely wishful thinking but a firm belief in God''s promises, which brings true gladness.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H8420", "description": "Defines the term and its significance in the Hebrew context."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 28, 28, 'kjv', 'but the expectation of the wicked shall perish', 45, 91, 'question', 'Reflection on Expectations', 'How does understanding the fate of the wicked''s expectations influence your daily choices and priorities? Reflecting on this can encourage a deeper commitment to living righteously, rooted in hope rather than fleeting desires.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 29, 29, 'kjv', 'The way of the Lord', 0, 19, 'connection', 'Paths of Righteousness', 'The phrase ''the way of the Lord'' resonates with Psalm 37:5, which states, ''Commit your way to the Lord; trust in him, and he will act.'' This connection emphasizes that following God''s path provides not only strength but also divine support in our endeavors. Both Scriptures highlight the importance of reliance on God for guidance in life.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 37:5", "description": "Illustrates the concept of trusting in God''s way."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 29, 29, 'kjv', 'is strength to the upright', 20, 46, 'theology', 'Divine Strength', 'This passage suggests that true strength is found in righteousness and alignment with God''s will. Many scholars believe that this aligns with the biblical principle that God equips the righteous with the fortitude needed to face life''s challenges. The notion of divine strength underscores the transformative power of living in accordance with God''s commands.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 29, 29, 'kjv', 'but destruction shall be to the workers of iniquity', 48, 99, 'question', 'Consequences of Choices', 'What does ''destruction'' imply about the ultimate fate of those who choose iniquity? Reflecting on this can lead to a deeper understanding of the moral implications of our actions and choices. How do the consequences of living contrary to God''s way manifest in our lives and the world around us?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 30, 30, 'kjv', 'The righteous shall never be removed', 0, 36, 'theology', 'Eternal Security of the Righteous', 'This passage suggests that the righteous possess a stability that is rooted in their relationship with God. Many scholars believe this reflects the broader biblical theme of eternal security found in texts such as John 10:28-29, which assures believers that they will never perish. This assurance provides a foundation for confidence in God’s promises and encourages a life lived in faithfulness.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 30, 30, 'kjv', 'but the wicked shall not inhabit the earth', 38, 80, 'connection', 'Judgment of the Wicked', 'This phrase connects to Psalm 37:9-11, where it states that evildoers will be cut off, but those who hope in the Lord will inherit the land. This connection highlights the theme of divine justice, affirming that ultimately, the wicked will not thrive or remain in God''s creation, while the righteous will dwell securely. This reinforces the moral order established by God.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 37:9-11", "description": "Affirms the fate of the wicked versus the righteous."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 30, 30, 'kjv', 'The righteous shall never be removed', 0, 36, 'question', 'Understanding Righteousness', 'What does it mean for the righteous to ''never be removed'' in the context of both earthly life and eternal life? How does this assurance shape your understanding of the trials and challenges faced by believers in today''s world?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 30, 30, 'kjv', 'but the wicked shall not inhabit the earth', 38, 80, 'greek', 'Key Hebrew Terms', 'רָשָׁע (rasha, H7563) - wicked, criminal, guilty. This term encapsulates those who act against God''s law, emphasizing their ultimate fate. The consequences of wickedness are starkly contrasted with the security of the righteous, underscoring the moral order in God''s creation.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H7563", "description": "Strong''s number for the term ''wicked.''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 31, 31, 'kjv', 'The mouth of the just bringeth forth wisdom', 0, 43, 'connection', 'Wisdom in Speech', 'This phrase connects with James 1:5, which encourages believers to ask God for wisdom. Both passages highlight the importance of wisdom, suggesting that those who are just and righteous are granted access to divine insight, enabling them to speak wisely. This reinforces the idea that righteousness aligns with wisdom.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 1:5", "description": "James encourages seeking wisdom from God, aligning with the theme of the just being wise."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 31, 31, 'kjv', 'but the froward tongue shall be cut out', 45, 84, 'theology', 'Consequences of Speech', 'This verse suggests a theological principle regarding the consequences of one''s words. Many scholars believe that the ''froward tongue'' represents not just careless speech but a heart disposition against God''s ways. This aligns with Jesus'' teaching in Matthew 12:36 about being held accountable for every careless word, emphasizing the moral weight of our speech.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew 12:36", "description": "Jesus teaches about the accountability of our words, connecting to the consequences mentioned in Proverbs."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 31, 31, 'kjv', 'The mouth of the just bringeth forth wisdom', 0, 43, 'question', 'Source of Wisdom', 'What does it mean for the mouth of the just to bring forth wisdom, and how can we cultivate a mouth that speaks wisely in our daily interactions? Consider how this relates to your own speech and the impact it has on those around you.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 31, 31, 'kjv', 'but the froward tongue shall be cut out', 45, 84, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Froward''', 'עִקְשָׁן (iqshan, H6141) - perverse, crooked. This Hebrew term indicates a deliberate turning away from righteousness, emphasizing that the froward tongue is not just unwise but actively opposes God''s ways. Recognizing this can deepen understanding of the consequences outlined in the verse.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H6141", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term used for ''froward''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 32, 32, 'kjv', 'The lips of the righteous know what is acceptable', 0, 49, 'connection', 'Righteous Speech', 'This phrase parallels James 3:10, which states, ''Out of the same mouth proceedeth blessing and cursing.'' It emphasizes the importance of speech reflecting one''s character. The righteous, having a relationship with God, naturally produce words that align with His will. This connection underscores the idea that righteousness influences not just actions but also words.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 3:10", "description": "Highlights the relationship between speech and character."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 32, 32, 'kjv', 'but the mouth of the wicked speaketh frowardness', 51, 99, 'theology', 'Nature of Wickedness', 'Many scholars believe this contrast between the righteous and the wicked illustrates a key theological principle: the outpouring of one''s inner nature. The wicked, lacking alignment with God''s righteousness, express themselves in ways that contradict divine standards. This teaches that our speech is a reflection of our spiritual state and relationship with God.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 32, 32, 'kjv', 'The lips of the righteous know what is acceptable', 0, 49, 'question', 'Understanding Acceptable Speech', 'What does it mean for the lips of the righteous to know what is acceptable? In what ways do you discern what is pleasing to God in your conversations? Reflecting on this can help you consider the alignment of your words with biblical principles.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 10, 32, 32, 'kjv', 'but the mouth of the wicked speaketh frowardness', 51, 99, 'greek', 'Frowardness in Greek', 'עִקְשׁוּת (iqshut, H6143) - perversity, stubbornness. The Hebrew word conveys a sense of moral distortion, indicating that the wicked''s speech is not just unwise but also intentionally contrary to God''s ways. Understanding this term deepens the insight into the nature of wickedness as it relates to speech.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H6143", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word used in this context."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 11, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'A false balance is abomination to the Lord:', 0, 43, 'connection', 'Cross-reference to Justice', 'This phrase resonates with Proverbs 20:10, which states, ''Divers weights, and divers measures, both of them are alike abomination to the Lord.'' This connection highlights God''s concern for fairness and integrity in dealings, underlining the moral imperative for just practices in commerce and life.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 20:10", "description": "Another verse emphasizing God''s disdain for dishonest practices."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 11, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'a just weight is his delight.', 48, 77, 'theology', 'God''s Preference for Justice', 'This passage suggests that God delights in justice and righteousness, reflecting a key theological principle found throughout Scripture. Many scholars believe that this aligns with the broader biblical theme of God''s desire for his people to act justly, as seen in Micah 6:8, which calls believers to ''do justly, love mercy, and walk humbly with God.''', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Micah 6:8", "description": "A foundational verse on justice and humility in the believer''s life."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 11, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'A false balance is abomination to the Lord:', 0, 43, 'question', 'Reflecting on Integrity', 'What does this warning against false balances reveal about the nature of integrity in your own life? How do you ensure that your actions align with God''s standards of fairness and honesty in your dealings with others?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 11, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'but a just weight is his delight.', 44, 77, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Just Weight''', 'צֶדֶק (tzedek, H6664) - righteousness, justice, fairness. This Hebrew term emphasizes the moral and ethical dimensions of living justly, which is central to this verse''s teaching about divine delight in just measures.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H6664", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word related to justice."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 11, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'When pride cometh, then cometh shame:', 0, 37, 'connection', 'Pride and Shame', 'This phrase resonates with Proverbs 16:18, which states, "Pride goeth before destruction, and a haughty spirit before a fall." Both verses emphasize the destructive nature of pride and the inevitable shame that follows. This connection underscores a biblical theme that warns against self-exaltation, reminding readers that humility is essential for wisdom.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 16:18", "description": "Highlights the relationship between pride and downfall."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 11, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'but with the lowly is wisdom.', 38, 67, 'theology', 'Humility and Wisdom', 'Many scholars believe this phrase illustrates a core biblical principle: true wisdom is found in humility. James 4:6 states, "God resisteth the proud, but giveth grace unto the humble," affirming that a humble heart opens oneself to divine wisdom. This passage reinforces the idea that spiritual insight is accessible to those who recognize their need for God.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 4:6", "description": "Connects humility with divine grace and wisdom."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 11, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'When pride cometh, then cometh shame:', 0, 37, 'question', 'Reflecting on Pride', 'What specific forms of pride do you encounter in your life, and how might they lead to shame? Reflecting on this can help identify areas where humility can improve your relationships and understanding of God’s wisdom.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 11, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'but with the lowly is wisdom.', 38, 67, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Lowly''', 'ταπεινός (tapeinos, G5011) - humble, lowly, or of a low degree. This term encapsulates the biblical view that true wisdom is aligned with those who are humble in spirit. It emphasizes that elevation in God''s kingdom comes through servanthood and lowliness rather than through pride.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G5011", "description": "Provides insight into the meaning of humility in the biblical context."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 11, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'The integrity of the upright shall guide them', 0, 45, 'connection', 'Guidance in Righteousness', 'This phrase echoes Psalm 25:9, where it states, ''The humble He guides in justice, and the humble He teaches His way.'' Both verses emphasize that integrity and humility are crucial for divine guidance. The connection highlights that those who live uprightly not only receive direction but also embody the principles of God’s justice.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 25:9", "description": "Illustrates the theme of divine guidance for the humble."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 11, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'but the perverseness of transgressors shall destroy them', 47, 103, 'theology', 'Consequences of Sin', 'Many scholars believe that this passage demonstrates the biblical principle of reaping what one sows, as reflected in Galatians 6:7. The ''perverseness'' of transgressors leads to their destruction, illustrating a fundamental teaching of personal responsibility in one''s moral actions and the inevitable consequences that follow.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Galatians 6:7", "description": "Reinforces the concept of reaping what you sow."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 11, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'The integrity of the upright shall guide them', 0, 45, 'question', 'Reflection on Integrity', 'What specific actions or decisions in your life reflect your integrity, and how can they serve as a guide in your daily choices? Consider how aligning your choices with uprightness can influence not just your path but also those around you.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 11, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'but the perverseness of transgressors shall destroy them', 47, 103, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Perverseness''', 'עַוְלָה (avlah, H5766) - iniquity, wickedness. This term captures the essence of moral distortion and wrongdoing. It emphasizes that the nature of one''s actions can lead to not just personal ruin but also broader consequences affecting community and society.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H5766", "description": "Strong''s number for ''perverseness''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 11, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'Riches profit not in the day of wrath:', 0, 38, 'connection', 'Wealth and Judgment', 'This phrase parallels Ezekiel 7:19, which states that wealth cannot save in times of calamity. Both verses highlight that material possessions are worthless when facing divine judgment. This connection emphasizes the transient nature of riches compared to spiritual integrity.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Ezekiel 7:19", "description": "Wealth cannot save from judgment."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 11, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'but righteousness delivereth from death.', 39, 79, 'theology', 'Righteousness and Salvation', 'Many scholars believe this verse encapsulates a core biblical theme: righteousness leads to life and deliverance from spiritual death. This concept resonates with New Testament teachings, especially Romans 10:10, where faith and righteousness are linked to salvation, thus reinforcing the idea that true security comes from moral integrity rather than material wealth.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Romans 10:10", "description": "Faith links righteousness to salvation."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 11, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'Riches profit not in the day of wrath:', 0, 38, 'question', 'Value of Wealth', 'What does this verse reveal about the ultimate value of wealth in the face of divine judgment? How can this understanding impact your priorities in life and your approach to material possessions?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 11, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'but righteousness delivereth from death.', 39, 79, 'greek', 'Righteousness Defined', 'צְדָקָה (tsedaqah, H6666) - righteousness, justice, rightness. This Hebrew term encompasses not just moral integrity but also social justice, implying that true righteousness extends beyond personal ethics to include one''s actions toward others and their welfare.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H6666", "description": "Strong''s number for righteousness."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 11, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'The righteousness of the perfect shall direct his way:', 0, 54, 'connection', 'Guidance in Righteousness', 'This phrase resonates with Psalms 37:23, which states, ''The steps of a good man are ordered by the Lord.'' Both verses emphasize that righteousness aligns one''s path with divine guidance, suggesting that living in accordance with God''s standards leads to a purposeful and directed life.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalms 37:23", "description": "Emphasizes divine guidance for the righteous."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 11, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'but the wicked shall fall by his own wickedness.', 55, 103, 'theology', 'Consequences of Wickedness', 'This verse reflects the doctrine of moral accountability, where one''s actions lead to inevitable consequences. Many scholars believe this aligns with the principle of divine justice, as articulated in Galatians 6:7, which warns that ''a man reaps what he sows.'' The idea is that wickedness leads to self-destruction, underlining God''s sovereign justice.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Galatians 6:7", "description": "Illustrates the principle of reaping what one sows."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 11, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'The righteousness of the perfect shall direct his way:', 0, 54, 'question', 'Path of Righteousness', 'How does understanding the ''righteousness of the perfect'' shape your daily choices? Reflect on specific instances where aligning your actions with God’s righteousness has directed your path or provided clarity in decision-making.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini');